Degenerative spinal conditions, such as osteoarthritis, can be visualized on a lumbar spine X-ray through the following findings:
- Narrowing of the intervertebral disc space;
- Osteophyte formation (bony spurs) at the margins of the vertebral bodies;
- Sclerosis (increased density) of subchondral bone;
- Vertebral body collapse or endplate irregularities;
- Facet joint hypertrophy and subluxation;
- Spinal stenosis (narrowing of the spinal canal).

Rationale:

Degenerative changes in the spine can be visualized on X-ray due to the structural changes that occur in the spine as a result of the degenerative process.  Narrowing of the intervertebral disc space is a common finding in osteoarthritis, as the disc loses height due to degeneration.  Osteophyte formation, or bony spurs, occur as the body attempts to stabilize the joint by creating new bone.  Sclerosis, or increased density, of subchondral bone is also seen as a result of the degenerative process.  Vertebral body collapse or endplate irregularities can also be seen in more advanced cases of
